@remark **********************************************************************
@remark @index compiling
@remark **********************************************************************

@node "aboutd2b" "About 'def2buttons'"

@{b}@{u}What is 'def2buttons'?@{uu}@{ub}


The @{b}def2buttons@{ub} program may be used to create your own PCAD @{"Tools" link "Tools.pic/main" 0}-window.
@{b}def2buttons@{ub} was a quick hack, rather than a comfortable interactive
GUI-builder.

PCAD uses the "pcad.icons" file, usually located in the "PCAD:" directory.
@{fg fill}@{"see 'Runtime Environment' for more details" link "pcad.guide/Umgebung" 0}@{fg text}
This file is a binary description of all buttons in the Tools-window.
As "pcad.icons" is a static description, the Tools-window will be static for
one PCAD session, i.e. no buttons can be added, removed or changed while
running PCAD.

The "pcad.icons" file was created by using the @{b}def2buttons@{ub} program. Each
button is described by one @{b}.def@{ub} file. @{b}def2buttons@{ub} reads all the @{b}.def@{ub}-files
and creates a compact binary file, that is equivalent to "pcad.icons".

There are two kinds of buttons:


@{u}Std. action buttons@{uu}

A std. action button is activated by clicking the icon (=button/gadget) with
the left mousebutton and releasing it, while the mousepointer is still inside
the icon (like every std. Amiga gadget). Then a single action is initiated.
This action is a PCAD commandstring, which is sent to the PCAD command
interpreter. As the commandstring is specified by each @{b}.def@{ub} file, @{fg highlight}you can
create your own button-menu, using any PCAD-commands, -scripts and/or Rexx
macros.@{fg text}
@{fg fill}@{"e.g. the 'Zoom Out' button" link "Tools.pic/main" 0} described by @{"zoomout.def" link "/Icons/zoomout.def/main" 0}@{fg text}


@{u}Toggleselect buttons@{uu}

These buttons behave like any std. Amiga toggleselect button. Activating the
button will change its state from selected to unselected and vice versa. The
@{b}.def@{ub} file contents @{b}two@{ub} commandstrings. One is sent to the command interpreter
when the button switches to @{i}selected,@{ui} the otherone when switching to
@{i}unselected.@{ui}
@{fg fill}@{"e.g. the 'Grid On/Off' button" link "Tools.pic/main" 0} described by @{"grid.def" link "/Icons/grid.def/main" 0}@{fg text}


@endnode

@remark **********************************************************************
@index compiling
@remark **********************************************************************

@node "compiletw" "The def2buttons compiler"

@{b}@{u}How to "compile" my own Tools-window@{ub}@{uu}

The directory @{b}PCAD:icons@{ub} holds all @{b}.def@{ub} and @{b}.pic@{ub} files that you need to compile
the std. @{"Tools" link "Tools.pic/main" 0}-window. There are two kinds of files:


@{u}.def files@{uu}

Each @{b}.def@{ub} file defines one button (gadget,icon). It also contents the filename
of the next button-description. By this, you get something like a linked list
of files. All @{b}.def@{ub} files together describe the @{i}Tools@{ui}-window.


@{u}.pic files@{uu}

The design (image) of each button is described by an IFF-ILBM file, that should
be 26x22 (width x height) pixels big. The extension @{b}.pic@{ub} is optional; you may
use any names. The IFF filename is specified by the @{b}.def@{ub} entry IMAGE=....


@{u}PCAD:def2buttons@{uu}

The "compiler" needs one argument:
   The filename of the 1st (top-left) button.

It reads all following (NEXT=...) @{b}.def@{ub} files and its @{b}.pic@{ub} files, creates the
buttons and saves a binary image to @{b}'test.picon'@{ub}. This binary image uses the
same format as @{b}'pcad.icons'@{ub}. The @{b}'test.picon'@{ub} result may be used as
@{b}'pcad.icons'@{ub} file. @{fg shine}Don't forget to make a backup-copy of the original
'pcad.icons' file!@{fg text}

If you wan't to "recompile" the std. Tools-window you show follow these steps:
   - you are using an Amiga shell
   - enter the directory PCAD:icons
      >cd PCAD:icons

   - call the @{b}'def2buttons'@{ub} "compiler"
      >def2buttons zoomout.def
   
   - a window will be opened (your workbench should be big enough!)
     and the buttons are created.
         @{i}@{fg shadow}(This takes about 2s on my A4000/40/25MHz, reading the
         files from HD; i.e. the buttons won't pop up immediately.
         This may take some time on slow Amiga's. Watch your HD-LED
         [or Floppy-LED] to check if the program still works.)@{ui}@{fg text}
     You may click the buttons to test them. The relating
     PCAD-command-sequence is written to the console.

   - close the window (by using the windows std. close-gadget)

   - if everything went well, the file 'test.picon' was created

   - backup your original 'pcad.icons' file
      e.g.
      >copy PCAD:pcad.icons PCAD:pcad.icons.bak

   - copy the 'test.picon' to 'PCAD:pcad.icons'
      >copy test.picon PCAD:pcad.icons

   - run PCAD to check the result
@endnode

@remark **********************************************************************
@index defiles
@remark **********************************************************************

@node "defiles" "The .def fileformat"

@{b}@{u}The .def button description@{uu}@{ub}

@{b}.def@{ub} files are ASCII files that describe the PCAD @{"Tools" link "Tools.pic/main" 0}-window buttons.
The 1st line must always be 'FILETYPE=ICON', the second line defines an unique
name of the button (e.g. 'NAME=ZOOMOUT'). Then the position is set by
'LEFTEDGE=<integer>' and 'TOPEDGE=<integer>'. If the button should be
top-aligned to its (left) neighbour's top you should use the special
"<integer>" 'ALIGN' (e.g. 'TOPEDGE=ALIGN'). You may use the constant 'GAP' to
create the std. margin between blocks (e.g. 'TOPEDGE=GAP'). If the left-
and/or top-edge are given by relative values, you have to specify this by
'XRELATIVE=TRUE' and/or 'YRELATIVE=TRUE'. These values are related to the
right bottom of the previous button.

The buttons image is specified by 'IMAGE=<name>' (e.g.'IMAGE=zoomout.pic').
This should be an IFF ILBM picture, 26x22 pixels big.

A button may be of the 'TOGGLESELECT=TRUE' kind, like the grid-button of the
std. Tools-window. If it is a toggleselect button, there are some more
options:
   SELECTED=TRUE           # this sets the initial state;
   SELECT=<PCAD-cmd's>     # called when the state changes to selected
   DESELECT=<PCAD-cmd's>   # called when the state changes to unselected

These options are mutual exclusive with the std. 'ACTION=..' definition.
   ACTION=<PCAD-cmd's>     # called when button is clicked

@{fg fill}@{"See <PCAD-cmd's> for more details." link "pcad.guide/Referenz" 0 }@{fg text}

'ROOT=TRUE' should be specified by the 1st (i.e. top-left) button of
the Tools-window. Its used for the future, declaring hierarchical
button-menu trees.

The next button, is specified by the @{b}.def@{ub} file of 'NEXT=..'
(e.g. 'NEXT=zoomin.def') building a linked list of button descriptions.

The '@{b}#@{ub}' sign initiates a comment.

Examples:
@{fg fill}
@{"'Zoom Out' button" link "Tools.pic/main" 0} described by @{"zoomout.def" link "/Icons/zoomout.def/main" 0}
@{"'Grid On/Off' button" link "Tools.pic/main" 0} described by @{"grid.def" link "/Icons/grid.def/main" 0}
@{fg text}
See other std. Tools-window definitions for more details.

@endnode
